1
00:00:06,791 --> 00:00:08,791
[mellow music playing]

2
00:00:18,541 --> 00:00:21,791
Attorney Kujo, this is the first time
I've seen you refuse a case.

3
00:00:22,458 --> 00:00:25,125
<i>Why'd you say no to Ms. Hanae Iemori?</i>

4
00:00:25,708 --> 00:00:29,416
Because down the line, it's a hassle
to be accused of a conflict of interest.

5
00:00:29,958 --> 00:00:33,583
You mean because you used to work
at Attorney Yamashiro's firm?

6
00:00:33,666 --> 00:00:36,958
I worked there for about five years
before I set up my own office.

7
00:00:38,041 --> 00:00:40,666
Has he always had a bad reputation?

8
00:00:40,750 --> 00:00:41,750
No.

9
00:00:42,583 --> 00:00:44,750
In the beginning,
he was liked and respected

10
00:00:44,833 --> 00:00:46,250
by everyone in the business.

11
00:00:46,333 --> 00:00:47,291
It's just…

12
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:50,750
He caught a big case
and became really well-known.

13
00:00:51,250 --> 00:00:54,166
So he started doing business
outside of his legal practice.

14
00:00:55,125 --> 00:00:57,083
Then, he went bust
and owed a ton of money.

15
00:00:57,166 --> 00:00:59,916
And he went to some unsavory types
to cover his debts?

16
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:03,291
After which, he found himself obliged
to offer them his services

17
00:01:03,375 --> 00:01:04,875
whenever they said so.

18
00:01:06,125 --> 00:01:08,250
Money is a scary thing.

19
00:01:08,875 --> 00:01:10,583
Seriously scary.

20
00:01:11,958 --> 00:01:13,291
[slurps]

21
00:01:14,166 --> 00:01:15,291
[sighs]

22
00:01:15,958 --> 00:01:17,958
[theme music playing]

23
00:01:56,708 --> 00:01:57,750
Ah.

24
00:01:57,833 --> 00:01:59,291
Hello, Attorney Nagaragi.

25
00:01:59,375 --> 00:02:00,625
Ah…

26
00:02:00,708 --> 00:02:02,666
My dear Kurama, it's been a while.

27
00:02:02,750 --> 00:02:05,291
I'm using Kujo as my name now.

28
00:02:05,375 --> 00:02:08,541
Oh, right, so I was told.
Your wife's last name, right?

29
00:02:09,041 --> 00:02:10,375
My ex-wife, sir.

30
00:02:10,458 --> 00:02:12,541
Ah. I beg your pardon.

31
00:02:12,625 --> 00:02:14,083
Is work going well?

32
00:02:14,166 --> 00:02:17,041
Thanks to everything you taught me,
I've been doing pretty well.

33
00:02:17,125 --> 00:02:18,916
So what can I do for you?

34
00:02:19,500 --> 00:02:22,958
I'm thinking about going after
this lawyer, an old friend of mine.

35
00:02:24,416 --> 00:02:27,708
If you're not sure whether to do it,
sounds like he's quite a good friend.

36
00:02:32,041 --> 00:02:35,000
All right, please just listen.
I'm going to talk to myself.

37
00:02:35,791 --> 00:02:36,708
Let's take a stroll.

38
00:02:36,791 --> 00:02:37,625
[Kujo] Sure.

39
00:02:37,708 --> 00:02:39,000
[somber music playing]

40
00:02:39,083 --> 00:02:41,208
"The law is nothing
but the ethical minimum."

41
00:02:41,708 --> 00:02:44,708
The famous words of Jellinek,
the German legal theorist.

42
00:02:45,250 --> 00:02:48,791
Things that strike us as immoral
aren't always going to be illegal.

43
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:52,750
Privately, people like to invoke ethics
to judge each other.

44
00:02:52,833 --> 00:02:54,583
The law doesn't work like that.

45
00:02:55,083 --> 00:02:57,541
We all have different ethical standards,
right?

46
00:02:58,833 --> 00:03:02,208
Sometimes the law can be unfeeling,
even cruel.

47
00:03:02,708 --> 00:03:06,333
If you abuse it,
it becomes completely immoral.

48
00:03:07,375 --> 00:03:09,208
You have to keep this straight
in your head.

49
00:03:10,541 --> 00:03:13,750
A lawyer is one who seeks to serve
the interest of their client.

50
00:03:14,375 --> 00:03:16,750
A client who knows
almost nothing about the law

51
00:03:16,833 --> 00:03:19,250
is at the complete mercy of their lawyer.

52
00:03:20,166 --> 00:03:23,458
So, of course,
they follow their lawyer's instructions,

53
00:03:23,541 --> 00:03:25,041
hand over a huge sum of money,

54
00:03:25,125 --> 00:03:27,500
and end up signing a document
that's totally unfair.

55
00:03:27,583 --> 00:03:30,458
Lawyers who are looking to get rich quick,

56
00:03:30,541 --> 00:03:33,791
when they should only be concerned about
whatever's best for their client,

57
00:03:33,875 --> 00:03:34,875
bring shame on us all.

58
00:03:35,666 --> 00:03:36,625
Yes, sir.

59
00:03:39,291 --> 00:03:40,666
So, Kujo…

60
00:03:41,875 --> 00:03:45,125
When the parents do evil deeds,
the son must step in.

61
00:03:47,333 --> 00:03:49,541
Yamashiro's evil deeds must be stopped.

62
00:03:53,583 --> 00:03:54,583
[music fades]

63
00:03:55,166 --> 00:03:56,583
[Yamashiro] Attorney Kujo.

64
00:03:56,666 --> 00:03:58,583
What do you say to some room service?

65
00:03:59,208 --> 00:04:01,041
That's okay. I'm fine.

66
00:04:02,750 --> 00:04:06,041
But you signed away all your assets
to your ex-wife, right?

67
00:04:06,125 --> 00:04:07,750
And you're living in a tent?

68
00:04:07,833 --> 00:04:09,333
Some hot food would do you good.

69
00:04:09,916 --> 00:04:12,083
These days,
I prefer to have one meal a day.

70
00:04:12,166 --> 00:04:13,000
[pants zipping]

71
00:04:13,083 --> 00:04:15,041
I find I concentrate better
with the fasting,

72
00:04:15,125 --> 00:04:17,708
and it also gives my digestive system
a break.

73
00:04:17,791 --> 00:04:19,750
The autophagy effect
increases one's immunity.

74
00:04:19,833 --> 00:04:22,000
What the hell is that? [chuckles]

75
00:04:22,083 --> 00:04:23,416
You gotta eat.

76
00:04:23,500 --> 00:04:27,041
A parent's always gonna worry
that their son isn't eating enough.

77
00:04:30,125 --> 00:04:32,916
[sighs] It's Yamashiro. Listen…

78
00:04:33,541 --> 00:04:34,791
Meat and bread.

79
00:04:34,875 --> 00:04:36,666
And send up some beer right away.

80
00:04:37,500 --> 00:04:38,500
I said beer!

81
00:04:38,583 --> 00:04:39,708
And make it snappy!

82
00:04:40,583 --> 00:04:41,750
Right.

83
00:04:41,833 --> 00:04:43,250
[phone receiver clatters]

84
00:04:43,333 --> 00:04:44,708
You eat meat in the morning?

85
00:04:45,416 --> 00:04:47,208
If you're in your prime,

86
00:04:47,291 --> 00:04:50,333
a bit of meat in the morning
gives you the boost you need.

87
00:04:51,666 --> 00:04:54,416
[sighs] So, what's on your mind?

88
00:04:58,125 --> 00:05:01,041
I am the lawyer representing
Shigenori Iemori's heir.

89
00:05:01,125 --> 00:05:03,666
I am calling upon you
as the executor of the will

90
00:05:04,333 --> 00:05:07,958
to show me, as required,
the inventory of the estate and the will.

91
00:05:08,041 --> 00:05:10,041
[unsettling music playing]

92
00:05:10,958 --> 00:05:11,791
[sighs]

93
00:05:11,875 --> 00:05:13,583
[Kujo] You know the one I mean.

94
00:05:14,250 --> 00:05:17,000
The guy who left his entire estate
to Kikogi,

95
00:05:17,500 --> 00:05:19,375
the company that runs the nursing home.

96
00:05:20,875 --> 00:05:23,166
When we ran a financial check
on the estate,

97
00:05:23,250 --> 00:05:26,208
we were told that you,
Attorney Yamashiro, as executor

98
00:05:26,291 --> 00:05:28,708
withdrew the entire amount
of the estate from the bank.

99
00:05:28,791 --> 00:05:32,833
I just duly and solemnly executed the will
as required by the law.

100
00:05:33,833 --> 00:05:37,000
But Mr. Iemori was
in an advanced state of dementia.

101
00:05:37,083 --> 00:05:38,875
There's no way he could have communicated.

102
00:05:39,625 --> 00:05:42,625
We will file a criminal complaint
for counterfeiting a document,

103
00:05:42,708 --> 00:05:44,166
uttering such a document,

104
00:05:44,250 --> 00:05:46,791
or criminal coercion,
depending on your response.

105
00:05:47,458 --> 00:05:49,083
You want the will?

106
00:05:49,166 --> 00:05:50,208
Okay.

107
00:05:53,500 --> 00:05:57,166
Here's the will written up all nice
and properly by the man himself.

108
00:05:57,250 --> 00:06:00,583
WILL: I, SHIGENORI IEMORI, HEREBY DECLARE
THE FOLLOWING AS MY WILL.

109
00:06:00,666 --> 00:06:04,125
THE EXECUTOR OF THE WILL: YUZO YAMASHIRO
TESTATOR: SHIGENORI IEMORI

110
00:06:04,208 --> 00:06:06,208
[upbeat music playing]

111
00:06:07,125 --> 00:06:10,250
Truth is, I don't mind fighting it out.

112
00:06:10,750 --> 00:06:14,541
But remember,
I care about you like you're my own son.

113
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:16,875
If you're unhappy,

114
00:06:17,375 --> 00:06:20,833
I could pay a lump sum equivalent
to the statutory reserved share.

115
00:06:21,958 --> 00:06:24,916
In that case,
the daughter gets around half.

116
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:27,333
Uh, that's around 200 million yen.

117
00:06:28,041 --> 00:06:28,875
What do you say?

118
00:06:29,958 --> 00:06:31,000
No, thanks.

119
00:06:32,083 --> 00:06:35,666
My client is adamant that
the entire estate be recovered in full.

120
00:06:36,916 --> 00:06:38,750
That's the only acceptable outcome.

121
00:06:39,333 --> 00:06:41,458
Well, Attorney Kujo…

122
00:06:42,583 --> 00:06:46,791
Are you… really going to cut off your nose
to spite your face?

123
00:06:49,958 --> 00:06:51,625
- Yes.
- Yes?

124
00:06:52,416 --> 00:06:53,500
Yes?!

125
00:06:56,791 --> 00:06:57,625
Yes.

126
00:06:57,708 --> 00:06:58,875
Yes, he says!

127
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:02,958
You think you could ever have made it
as a lawyer without my help?

128
00:07:03,041 --> 00:07:04,125
Show your second father some respect!

129
00:07:04,208 --> 00:07:05,833
I'm just doing what he taught me.

130
00:07:07,875 --> 00:07:10,083
Siding with my client no matter what.

131
00:07:12,833 --> 00:07:15,625
[Ms. Iemori] I don't understand
all your mumbo jumbo.

132
00:07:15,708 --> 00:07:19,041
- [Kujo] <i>Well, as I explained to you--</i>
- I don't wanna hear your explanations.

133
00:07:19,125 --> 00:07:21,000
Just make sure
you get back the whole thing.

134
00:07:21,083 --> 00:07:22,916
[Kujo] <i>Yes, yes. </i>[sighs]

135
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:24,500
One "yes" will do.

136
00:07:25,875 --> 00:07:28,958
[Karasuma] You took Ms. Iemori's case.
I'm impressed.

137
00:07:29,541 --> 00:07:31,083
There's no going back now.

138
00:07:31,625 --> 00:07:33,041
[Kujo] I realize that.

139
00:07:34,416 --> 00:07:37,125
So, do you have a plan
for taking on your old mentor?

140
00:07:37,708 --> 00:07:40,000
I'm working on a few ideas.

141
00:07:40,625 --> 00:07:42,750
But you're at a complete disadvantage.

142
00:07:44,083 --> 00:07:47,625
There's even a testament written
and signed by the late Mr. Iemori.

143
00:07:48,500 --> 00:07:52,500
Except that Mr. Shigenori Iemori was
in the throes of dementia.

144
00:07:52,583 --> 00:07:55,791
So we have to ask, could he write his will
of his own free will?

145
00:07:55,875 --> 00:07:59,375
Well, his daughter, Hanae, is convinced
that someone forced him to write it.

146
00:07:59,875 --> 00:08:02,666
If only we could prove it
one way or another.

147
00:08:04,666 --> 00:08:07,166
[Kujo] That's a pretty tall order.

148
00:08:07,250 --> 00:08:08,125
[sighs]

149
00:08:09,041 --> 00:08:11,125
After all, the old fox we're up against

150
00:08:11,208 --> 00:08:13,250
knows every trick in the book.

151
00:08:13,333 --> 00:08:14,666
I'm still surprised.

152
00:08:16,333 --> 00:08:17,375
Surprised?

153
00:08:17,458 --> 00:08:19,625
I was sure you'd refuse the case.

154
00:08:20,833 --> 00:08:22,333
Why did you take it on?

155
00:08:26,958 --> 00:08:27,791
[scoffs softly]

156
00:08:29,875 --> 00:08:30,875
Now then,

157
00:08:31,666 --> 00:08:32,750
let's get going.

158
00:08:34,416 --> 00:08:36,416
[inquisitive music playing]

159
00:09:08,125 --> 00:09:12,125
KIKOGI NURSING HOME, INC.
KIKO

160
00:09:20,458 --> 00:09:22,541
[man 1] Oh. Hello, there. Welcome!

161
00:09:23,250 --> 00:09:24,958
You must be the lawyer.

162
00:09:25,041 --> 00:09:28,000
It turns out that President Sugawara
is just a little late today.

163
00:09:28,083 --> 00:09:30,333
While you're waiting,
perhaps I could show you both around?

164
00:09:31,250 --> 00:09:33,041
Sure, that would be nice.

165
00:09:33,125 --> 00:09:34,916
[man 1] Okay. Right this way.

166
00:09:37,833 --> 00:09:39,791
Over here is the games room.

167
00:09:40,333 --> 00:09:42,083
The residents love to come here

168
00:09:42,791 --> 00:09:44,833
just to hang out and have fun together.

169
00:09:49,041 --> 00:09:50,583
The facility is clean,

170
00:09:50,666 --> 00:09:52,666
and the residents seem
to be in a great mood.

171
00:09:52,750 --> 00:09:54,208
[man 1] Thank you. We do our best.

172
00:09:54,291 --> 00:09:55,833
- [caregiver] Excuse me.
- [man 1] Oh.

173
00:09:56,333 --> 00:09:57,166
Hello.

174
00:09:57,250 --> 00:09:58,125
Hello.

175
00:09:58,208 --> 00:10:00,375
[indistinct chatter]

176
00:10:00,458 --> 00:10:04,041
[man 1] "A bright and happy future starts
when we have believing hearts."

177
00:10:04,125 --> 00:10:05,708
The president created that motto himself.

178
00:10:06,625 --> 00:10:09,875
Even the elderly,
if they have faith in a bright future,

179
00:10:09,958 --> 00:10:11,875
can feel a new will to live.

180
00:10:12,375 --> 00:10:13,666
[Karasuma] I see.

181
00:10:14,750 --> 00:10:16,250
[man 1] Today, they're coloring.

182
00:10:35,250 --> 00:10:36,625
[chain rattles]

183
00:10:39,458 --> 00:10:40,291
[man 2] Hey.

184
00:10:40,375 --> 00:10:41,333
[music ends]

185
00:10:41,416 --> 00:10:43,458
Nobody's allowed in there.
It's off-limits.

186
00:10:43,541 --> 00:10:45,208
Uh… I'm sorry.

187
00:10:45,833 --> 00:10:47,583
[man 1] Oh! Mr. Kuga.

188
00:10:52,208 --> 00:10:53,083
Oh.

189
00:10:53,666 --> 00:10:55,208
You must be Attorney Kujo, huh?

190
00:10:56,291 --> 00:10:57,166
That's right.

191
00:10:57,250 --> 00:10:59,708
President Sugawara is busy today
and can't meet with you.

192
00:11:00,875 --> 00:11:02,125
Will that be all, then?

193
00:11:02,208 --> 00:11:04,291
But we have an appointment.

194
00:11:05,250 --> 00:11:06,666
Please make another.

195
00:11:06,750 --> 00:11:07,916
Understood.

196
00:11:08,833 --> 00:11:10,625
Time to go, Mr. Karasuma.

197
00:11:10,708 --> 00:11:12,708
What? But we've barely seen anything yet.

198
00:11:12,791 --> 00:11:13,750
[Kujo] Let's go.

199
00:11:17,083 --> 00:11:19,208
[tense music playing]

200
00:11:27,375 --> 00:11:28,458
[music ends]

201
00:11:30,041 --> 00:11:31,583
- [car beeping]
- So that's it?

202
00:11:33,166 --> 00:11:36,250
They had no intention of showing us
the important area anyway.

203
00:11:36,333 --> 00:11:37,958
Yeah, you're probably right.

204
00:11:38,750 --> 00:11:39,833
Mr. Karasuma.

205
00:11:39,916 --> 00:11:40,750
Yeah?

206
00:11:41,250 --> 00:11:43,833
I have a… small favor to ask.

207
00:11:50,375 --> 00:11:52,375
[tense music playing]

208
00:11:59,333 --> 00:12:05,458
A bright and happy future starts
when we have believing hearts.

209
00:12:27,625 --> 00:12:28,625
[music ends]

210
00:12:29,666 --> 00:12:32,125
Hey, there, boys!

211
00:12:32,208 --> 00:12:33,791
[laughs]

212
00:12:34,375 --> 00:12:38,541
You can't do that, Mr. Udagawa.
No excursions allowed without our say-so.

213
00:12:38,625 --> 00:12:40,083
You broke the rules,

214
00:12:40,166 --> 00:12:43,458
so that means
you're confined to bed for a week.

215
00:12:43,541 --> 00:12:44,666
[groans]

216
00:12:44,750 --> 00:12:46,375
I'm really hungry.

217
00:12:47,375 --> 00:12:50,541
[man] Sure thing.
Curry or ramen? What'll it be?

218
00:12:50,625 --> 00:12:52,708
I don't want any more cold food.

219
00:12:52,791 --> 00:12:56,541
I want something hot,
like rice and miso soup.

220
00:12:56,625 --> 00:12:59,541
[man] The curry and ramen here
are best when they're cold.

221
00:13:00,166 --> 00:13:01,875
[Kuga] You should quit being so selfish.

222
00:13:02,875 --> 00:13:03,791
Hey.

223
00:13:04,416 --> 00:13:06,666
You want to end up like Iwai
in the bed beside you?

224
00:13:06,750 --> 00:13:09,875
Want me to put a hole in your stomach?
Give you food in a tube?

225
00:13:10,708 --> 00:13:11,708
No.

226
00:13:12,291 --> 00:13:14,041
[Kuga] Then you're gonna have to stand it.

227
00:13:15,583 --> 00:13:17,208
Bright and happy future

228
00:13:17,875 --> 00:13:20,416
starts when we have believing hearts.

229
00:13:20,500 --> 00:13:21,333
Go on.

230
00:13:21,916 --> 00:13:25,708
A bright and happy… future starts with--

231
00:13:25,791 --> 00:13:29,916
- Put some heart into it!
- A bright and happy future starts--

232
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:32,000
[man] Louder! I can't hear you!

233
00:13:32,083 --> 00:13:36,500
[Udagawa] A bright and happy future starts
when we have believing hearts!

234
00:13:36,583 --> 00:13:37,916
[man] Okay, one more time.

235
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:39,541
[Udagawa] A bright and happy--

236
00:13:59,166 --> 00:14:01,041
[man] Udagawa's done with his meal.

237
00:14:01,541 --> 00:14:02,500
[Kuga] Right.

238
00:14:03,083 --> 00:14:04,458
Did he eat everything?

239
00:14:05,041 --> 00:14:07,541
[man] Yeah,
after I forced the curry down his throat.

240
00:14:08,041 --> 00:14:11,208
Man, I tried that stuff once.
I literally thought I was gonna die.

241
00:14:11,291 --> 00:14:12,791
[bag rustling]

242
00:14:12,875 --> 00:14:14,083
Working here…

243
00:14:15,583 --> 00:14:16,541
You used to it?

244
00:14:17,791 --> 00:14:18,708
Yeah.

245
00:14:19,666 --> 00:14:22,750
The workers get to do what they want.
The job's really cool.

246
00:14:24,625 --> 00:14:27,583
Sugawara thinks caregiving is a business,

247
00:14:27,666 --> 00:14:29,583
and we should keep our feelings out of it.

248
00:14:29,666 --> 00:14:31,958
If the residents are confined
to the facility,

249
00:14:32,041 --> 00:14:34,875
it cuts down on travel costs
for visits to their family.

250
00:14:35,583 --> 00:14:39,041
And the compensation will keep coming in
until the residents die.

251
00:14:39,708 --> 00:14:41,625
He said it's like a subscription.

252
00:14:41,708 --> 00:14:43,750
Subscription. [chuckles]

253
00:14:43,833 --> 00:14:44,833
For real.

254
00:14:45,541 --> 00:14:47,750
With old folks just sitting
on loads of dough,

255
00:14:47,833 --> 00:14:49,833
the point is to get them hooked, he says,

256
00:14:49,916 --> 00:14:52,625
and use the caregiving
as a way to suck them dry.

257
00:14:52,708 --> 00:14:55,041
[laughs]

258
00:14:55,125 --> 00:14:57,375
He sure squeezed Iemori like a lemon,

259
00:14:57,458 --> 00:14:59,083
the one who died the other day.

260
00:15:00,083 --> 00:15:01,125
Iemori, huh?

261
00:15:02,916 --> 00:15:04,500
He was a lot of work.

262
00:15:04,583 --> 00:15:06,375
He was pig-headed.

263
00:15:06,458 --> 00:15:08,583
I punched him so hard I cracked his rib.

264
00:15:08,666 --> 00:15:10,125
[chuckles]

265
00:15:10,208 --> 00:15:12,791
You know, my boss got me to do this,
uh, funny thing.

266
00:15:12,875 --> 00:15:16,333
I had to make Iemori write the same
sentences over and over. [chuckles]

267
00:15:16,916 --> 00:15:19,208
Sometimes he'd put up a fight
and refuse to do it.

268
00:15:19,291 --> 00:15:22,125
Every time he said no,
I flicked his broken rib just like that.

269
00:15:22,208 --> 00:15:23,458
[chuckles]

270
00:15:24,541 --> 00:15:27,166
The look he got on his face was hilarious.
I made a video of it.

271
00:15:27,250 --> 00:15:28,375
You wanna see it?

272
00:15:28,875 --> 00:15:29,708
Sure.

273
00:15:29,791 --> 00:15:33,583
- [man] <i>Executor! The executor of the will!</i>
- [Iemori groaning in pain]

274
00:15:33,666 --> 00:15:34,875
[man chuckles]

275
00:15:34,958 --> 00:15:37,208
[man laughs on video]

276
00:15:37,291 --> 00:15:39,208
[man] <i>You got that? Go on! Write it!</i>

277
00:15:39,291 --> 00:15:40,791
<i>C'mon, c'mon, c'mon, c'mon, c'mon!</i>

278
00:15:40,875 --> 00:15:42,833
<i>I… I can't breathe.</i>

279
00:15:42,916 --> 00:15:45,125
- [Sugawara] Give me that.
- [Iemori groaning on video]

280
00:15:45,208 --> 00:15:46,208
Uh…

281
00:15:47,583 --> 00:15:50,250
- [Iemori groaning in pain]
- [man on video] <i>Testator.</i>

282
00:15:50,333 --> 00:15:53,125
You mean you actually
kept evidence of abuse?

283
00:15:53,208 --> 00:15:55,125
President Sugawara. I…

284
00:15:57,666 --> 00:15:58,750
[tense music playing]

285
00:15:58,833 --> 00:16:02,208
[Sugawara] Tell me, do you save
your photos and videos to the cloud?

286
00:16:02,708 --> 00:16:04,000
No, sir.

287
00:16:08,458 --> 00:16:09,541
[man exhales shakily]

288
00:16:12,791 --> 00:16:15,291
[Sugawara] Trouble is,
these days, smartphones can survive

289
00:16:15,375 --> 00:16:16,625
being submerged in water.

290
00:16:18,958 --> 00:16:20,958
[mournful music playing]

291
00:16:35,083 --> 00:16:36,791
When you get to the top,

292
00:16:37,291 --> 00:16:38,708
drop your phone.

293
00:16:39,333 --> 00:16:40,458
And it better break!

294
00:16:42,333 --> 00:16:44,125
[man hesitating] Yes, sir!

295
00:16:44,208 --> 00:16:45,708
[whimpering]

296
00:16:46,875 --> 00:16:49,375
Mr. Sugawara, I'll throw your coffee away.

297
00:16:52,458 --> 00:16:55,250
I didn't bother to wash my hands
after I used the john.

298
00:16:55,791 --> 00:16:57,750
There's gotta be a lot of germs in there.

299
00:16:58,250 --> 00:16:59,333
That's nasty.

300
00:16:59,416 --> 00:17:00,333
- Drink it.
- [music ends]

301
00:17:01,875 --> 00:17:02,791
Huh?

302
00:17:10,416 --> 00:17:11,250
You heard me.

303
00:17:11,333 --> 00:17:13,333
[low-key music playing]

304
00:17:14,416 --> 00:17:15,291
Yes, sir.

305
00:17:28,333 --> 00:17:31,916
Whenever I look at
the half-dead old folks in this place,

306
00:17:32,416 --> 00:17:35,625
it always makes me think
they're a lot like this country of mine.

307
00:17:36,458 --> 00:17:38,958
This country? Japan, you mean?

308
00:17:40,291 --> 00:17:44,083
With more and more elderly people,
Japan's taxes come from the workers,

309
00:17:44,166 --> 00:17:46,500
which is barely half the population.

310
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:50,375
The rich know how to avoid taxes
and hide their wealth.

311
00:17:50,458 --> 00:17:52,208
The burden will fall on the working stiffs

312
00:17:52,291 --> 00:17:54,625
who have their taxes squeezed out
at the source.

313
00:17:54,708 --> 00:17:56,458
[man] I made it to the top!

314
00:18:00,333 --> 00:18:01,541
Do it!

315
00:18:01,625 --> 00:18:03,583
[whimpering] Yes, sir!

316
00:18:03,666 --> 00:18:06,208
[Sugawara] What? I can't hear you!

317
00:18:07,750 --> 00:18:08,708
[whimpers]

318
00:18:08,791 --> 00:18:10,208
Yes, sir!

319
00:18:23,250 --> 00:18:24,625
[phone smashes]

320
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:28,416
[Sugawara] Kuga,

321
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:30,541
give me that coffee.

322
00:18:35,500 --> 00:18:38,750
We're gonna milk this thing
as much as we can,

323
00:18:38,833 --> 00:18:41,458
then we'll get the hell out
of this dying country,

324
00:18:42,125 --> 00:18:45,083
relocate to someplace
that's up-and-coming,

325
00:18:45,583 --> 00:18:47,666
and just kick back and relax.

326
00:18:51,625 --> 00:18:52,500
[slurps]

327
00:18:54,916 --> 00:18:56,916
[gulping loudly]

328
00:18:58,083 --> 00:18:59,375
[sighs]

329
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:08,208
Sharing this cup makes us brothers.

330
00:19:11,041 --> 00:19:13,000
You turn on me and I'll kill you.

331
00:19:13,083 --> 00:19:15,083
[music fades]

332
00:19:16,750 --> 00:19:17,875
Yes, sir.

333
00:19:20,916 --> 00:19:22,791
BEIJING RESTAURANT
CHINESE CUISINE

334
00:19:22,875 --> 00:19:24,291
[waitress] Thank you very much.

335
00:19:24,375 --> 00:19:25,833
[owner] Welcome! Come on in.

336
00:19:25,916 --> 00:19:27,666
[Karasuma] Eat as much as you want.

337
00:19:27,750 --> 00:19:29,208
[Yakushimae] It'd be nice to take me

338
00:19:29,291 --> 00:19:30,750
to a high-end sushi place for once.

339
00:19:30,833 --> 00:19:33,958
Or a teppanyaki restaurant
where the chef cooks in front of you.

340
00:19:34,041 --> 00:19:36,291
We always end up going
to this kind of place.

341
00:19:36,916 --> 00:19:37,958
Hang on there.

342
00:19:38,041 --> 00:19:41,625
Ms. Yakushimae!
This kind of place? That's a little rude!

343
00:19:41,708 --> 00:19:43,250
Come on. Take a look around you!

344
00:19:43,333 --> 00:19:45,541
The walls are plastered
with fake autographs!

345
00:19:45,625 --> 00:19:47,750
[owner] Those autographs are real.

346
00:19:47,833 --> 00:19:49,416
What do you mean, fake?

347
00:19:49,916 --> 00:19:52,750
Morgan Freeman.
No way he ate in this place.

348
00:19:52,833 --> 00:19:54,041
He used the washroom!

349
00:19:54,125 --> 00:19:56,375
Hey, Attorney Karasuma.
This is fraud, right?

350
00:19:56,458 --> 00:19:59,208
- [Karasuma] Huh?
- Maybe I'll sue this restaurant.

351
00:19:59,291 --> 00:20:00,166
Okay, come on.

352
00:20:00,250 --> 00:20:03,541
When we're through with this case,
we'll get Mr. Kujo to take us out.

353
00:20:04,750 --> 00:20:06,208
I'm holding you to that.

354
00:20:07,625 --> 00:20:09,666
So, did you find out anything
about Ms. Iemori's case?

355
00:20:09,750 --> 00:20:10,625
[Yakushimae] Oh.

356
00:20:12,958 --> 00:20:15,708
The late Mr. Iemori used to run
a famous jewelry store.

357
00:20:15,791 --> 00:20:16,875
You heard about that?

358
00:20:17,708 --> 00:20:20,708
Yeah, I knew he was the owner
of a jewelry store.

359
00:20:21,208 --> 00:20:22,625
Not that it was famous, though.

360
00:20:22,708 --> 00:20:25,333
Put it this way.
The store wasn't a success.

361
00:20:25,416 --> 00:20:29,083
It was famous for having no customers
and somehow not going out of business.

362
00:20:29,166 --> 00:20:31,375
Yeah, well, we've heard that story before.

363
00:20:31,458 --> 00:20:34,666
But the family owned a lot of land,
so there was no shortage of money.

364
00:20:35,166 --> 00:20:38,833
And I guess she got into some disputes
with her younger brother and his wife.

365
00:20:38,916 --> 00:20:39,750
IEMORI

366
00:20:40,416 --> 00:20:43,666
<i>Her younger brother is named Keisuke.</i>
<i>He's an accountant.</i>

367
00:20:44,166 --> 00:20:45,041
[woman] Hey!

368
00:20:45,708 --> 00:20:47,208
That's bugging the neighbors.

369
00:20:47,291 --> 00:20:49,708
- [Yakushimae] <i>His wife's name is Saeko.</i>
- Here.

370
00:20:50,291 --> 00:20:52,375
[Yakushimae] <i>Before Shigenori</i>
<i>developed dementia,</i>

371
00:20:52,458 --> 00:20:55,625
it seems that Keisuke
left with his mother.

372
00:20:56,375 --> 00:20:59,541
Leaving Hanae to take care of her dad…
all alone?

373
00:20:59,625 --> 00:21:00,666
That's right.

374
00:21:01,333 --> 00:21:02,375
It can't have been easy.

375
00:21:02,458 --> 00:21:05,333
He would wander about aimlessly
and turn the house upside down.

376
00:21:06,041 --> 00:21:08,333
I asked a friend of mine
who's a caregiver.

377
00:21:08,958 --> 00:21:12,458
She thinks Shigenori must've had
a pretty severe case of dementia.

378
00:21:12,541 --> 00:21:13,958
How severe?

379
00:21:14,541 --> 00:21:16,083
It goes like this.

380
00:21:16,166 --> 00:21:21,333
Preclinical, early, middle, advanced.
Those are the four stages.

381
00:21:22,208 --> 00:21:25,708
Mr. Shigenori's cognitive abilities
had declined.

382
00:21:25,791 --> 00:21:27,833
He was unable to recognize people

383
00:21:27,916 --> 00:21:31,083
or understand words,
so he had advanced dementia.

384
00:21:32,458 --> 00:21:33,666
Advanced…

385
00:21:33,750 --> 00:21:35,041
[melancholy music playing]

386
00:21:35,625 --> 00:21:37,125
So that's 1,012 yen.

387
00:21:37,208 --> 00:21:38,208
What?

388
00:21:38,291 --> 00:21:39,708
One thousand and twelve.

389
00:21:39,791 --> 00:21:42,291
- Okay, my dear. Give me a second.
- Okay.

390
00:21:42,375 --> 00:21:46,791
[Ms. Iemori] <i>I have got things to do.</i>
<i>Look at this doddering old biddy.</i>

391
00:21:46,875 --> 00:21:50,000
<i>Try getting your wallet ready</i>
<i>before you reach the register.</i>

392
00:21:50,083 --> 00:21:51,541
- [customer] I'd like to…
- [clerk] Yes.

393
00:21:51,625 --> 00:21:54,250
I'd like to use this to pay for it.

394
00:21:54,333 --> 00:21:56,833
[clerk] I’m very sorry,
but we don’t accept that…

395
00:21:56,916 --> 00:21:59,916
[Ms. Iemori] <i>Wherever you look here,</i>
<i>it's just old people.</i>

396
00:22:05,875 --> 00:22:08,375
MENTHOL RUB

397
00:22:08,875 --> 00:22:10,375
Bad taste.

398
00:22:10,458 --> 00:22:12,125
[clerk] Please don't go down this aisle.

399
00:22:14,041 --> 00:22:15,208
- [Mr. Iemori] Bad.
- Excuse me.

400
00:22:15,291 --> 00:22:16,916
Excuse me. Excuse me.

401
00:22:19,916 --> 00:22:20,750
Dad!

402
00:22:20,833 --> 00:22:22,458
Oh! No, no, no. No, no.

403
00:22:22,541 --> 00:22:25,458
Dad, let's go home.
Let's go home. Let's go home.

404
00:22:25,541 --> 00:22:26,958
[clerk] Excuse me. I'm sorry.

405
00:22:27,041 --> 00:22:28,583
- Ma'am, ma'am!
- I'm sorry.

406
00:22:28,666 --> 00:22:31,125
- You're gonna have to pay for that.
- I'm sorry. Come on. Oh no!

407
00:22:31,208 --> 00:22:33,583
- Give me the answer.
- Dad, stop it. Stop it. Stop it.

408
00:22:33,666 --> 00:22:35,625
Give me the answer!

409
00:22:35,708 --> 00:22:38,250
Dad. No, no, no, no.

410
00:22:38,333 --> 00:22:40,625
- [liquid tinkling]
- Dad?

411
00:22:41,791 --> 00:22:43,500
[woman 1] Hey, what is that?
Do you smell it?

412
00:22:44,791 --> 00:22:47,250
[woman 2] Oh my God.
It stinks. What the hell?

413
00:22:47,333 --> 00:22:49,166
- [woman 1] Something stinks.
- [woman 2] It does.

414
00:22:49,250 --> 00:22:50,291
[woman 1] What is it?

415
00:22:51,208 --> 00:22:52,166
[woman 2] No way.

416
00:22:52,875 --> 00:22:55,375
[woman 1] That's disgusting. Let's go.

417
00:23:15,416 --> 00:23:17,291
There's an open cash there.

418
00:23:17,375 --> 00:23:19,375
[music fades]

419
00:23:22,750 --> 00:23:24,458
Good morning, Mr. Kujo.

420
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:27,083
[Kujo] Good morning, Mr. Karasuma.

421
00:23:32,083 --> 00:23:33,250
What happened here?

422
00:23:33,875 --> 00:23:35,958
The office is a total disaster.

423
00:23:36,791 --> 00:23:39,083
Don't tell me… The cops raided us?

424
00:23:39,583 --> 00:23:40,583
Uh…

425
00:23:42,833 --> 00:23:44,250
It was Black Thunder.

426
00:23:46,375 --> 00:23:49,000
When she doesn't get enough exercise,
she gets wound up,

427
00:23:49,083 --> 00:23:50,833
and this is what happens.

428
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:53,666
If we don't find him a new owner soon,

429
00:23:53,750 --> 00:23:56,083
we're gonna have to shut down
our practice.

430
00:23:56,666 --> 00:23:58,416
So, how did it go?

431
00:23:58,500 --> 00:24:00,458
The background check on Ms. Iemori.

432
00:24:00,958 --> 00:24:04,166
It sounds like
Mr. Shigenori's dementia was quite severe.

433
00:24:04,666 --> 00:24:07,791
In my opinion, he was too far gone
to be able to write a will.

434
00:24:08,291 --> 00:24:09,208
I see.

435
00:24:10,833 --> 00:24:14,875
It could be that someone copied
Mr. Shigenori's handwriting

436
00:24:14,958 --> 00:24:16,375
and forged the will.

437
00:24:18,458 --> 00:24:19,291
[sighs]

438
00:24:19,375 --> 00:24:21,083
The only thing is…

439
00:24:29,583 --> 00:24:30,666
This…

440
00:24:30,750 --> 00:24:32,500
It's Mr. Shigenori Iemori.

441
00:24:36,958 --> 00:24:39,083
[Karasuma] He's writing the will himself.

442
00:24:39,166 --> 00:24:40,958
[tense music playing]

443
00:24:41,041 --> 00:24:43,458
[Yamashiro] I sent this
to our opponent's lawyer.

444
00:24:43,958 --> 00:24:45,250
I see.

445
00:24:49,166 --> 00:24:52,916
I gotta admit, 3,000 yen
gets you a tasty burger.

446
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:54,083
Good, isn't it?

447
00:24:54,875 --> 00:24:56,791
The hotel's specialty, I guess.

448
00:24:57,416 --> 00:24:58,500
So…

449
00:24:59,750 --> 00:25:02,458
You're telling me we're all good,
Mr. Yamashiro?

450
00:25:02,541 --> 00:25:04,125
Mr. Sugawara,

451
00:25:04,208 --> 00:25:05,791
you shouldn't worry.

452
00:25:06,458 --> 00:25:08,208
In legal disputes,

453
00:25:08,291 --> 00:25:11,500
ideally, you wanna get your opponent
to give in to you

454
00:25:11,583 --> 00:25:13,041
without hurting them.

455
00:25:14,166 --> 00:25:15,833
Sure, we could beat them in court,

456
00:25:15,916 --> 00:25:18,583
but a showy victory is beside the point.

457
00:25:19,541 --> 00:25:25,041
The best kind of settlement comes
with no applause, no glory.

458
00:25:27,500 --> 00:25:28,666
It means

459
00:25:28,750 --> 00:25:31,375
it's important to win
without having to fight.

460
00:25:33,375 --> 00:25:35,458
I showed him parental love.

461
00:25:37,833 --> 00:25:40,375
But Attorney Kujo showed me his fangs.

462
00:25:40,458 --> 00:25:41,416
[music ends]

463
00:25:42,500 --> 00:25:44,791
He lost the battle before it started.

464
00:25:44,875 --> 00:25:46,541
[upbeat music playing]

465
00:25:46,625 --> 00:25:48,625
[duct tape tearing]

466
00:25:52,833 --> 00:25:54,375
[Ms. Iemori] Ah, Father…

467
00:25:55,375 --> 00:25:57,083
How could this possibly have happened?

468
00:25:57,666 --> 00:26:00,625
[Kujo] It was probably made
under Attorney Yamashiro's instructions.

469
00:26:01,291 --> 00:26:03,041
Since it's written by hand,
the will is valid.

470
00:26:03,125 --> 00:26:04,750
He wants to resolve the issue quickly.

471
00:26:04,833 --> 00:26:06,208
He's looking for a settlement.

472
00:26:06,791 --> 00:26:10,000
A settlement?
You mean, I'm supposed to accept half?

473
00:26:10,083 --> 00:26:12,250
There's no way I'm gonna agree to that.

474
00:26:12,333 --> 00:26:15,500
Attorney Yamashiro has assembled
a strong case, you know.

475
00:26:16,500 --> 00:26:18,875
He's got the recording
of the will being written.

476
00:26:18,958 --> 00:26:22,125
I'm sure the primary care doctor
is conspiring with the nursing home.

477
00:26:22,208 --> 00:26:25,458
The doctor will hold back any medical
records that could weaken their case.

478
00:26:26,041 --> 00:26:29,375
It's like the perfect crime.
There isn't a scrap of evidence.

479
00:26:29,458 --> 00:26:31,458
There's nothing we can do about it.

480
00:26:32,333 --> 00:26:34,791
In a court of law,
the evidence gives Attorney Yamashiro

481
00:26:34,875 --> 00:26:37,375
a huge advantage.
He's got an ironclad defense.

482
00:26:38,833 --> 00:26:40,750
Ironclad indeed.

483
00:26:42,458 --> 00:26:43,291
Ms. Iemori.

484
00:26:44,291 --> 00:26:47,708
Considering how expensive
a drawn-out trial can get,

485
00:26:47,791 --> 00:26:50,375
accepting their offer
of the statutory reserved share

486
00:26:50,458 --> 00:26:51,875
would be the wise course of action.

487
00:26:51,958 --> 00:26:52,875
No, no, no, no, no.

488
00:26:52,958 --> 00:26:55,333
No way in hell. Absolutely not.

489
00:26:55,416 --> 00:26:59,333
I just give away the inheritance?
To some crooks who run a nursing home?

490
00:26:59,416 --> 00:27:02,166
All of it…
Is there no way to get it all back?

491
00:27:04,583 --> 00:27:05,875
If there is a way,

492
00:27:07,166 --> 00:27:08,833
it would have to be
to catch them off guard.

493
00:27:10,666 --> 00:27:11,916
Catch them off guard?

494
00:27:12,625 --> 00:27:16,208
Why does Attorney Yamashiro go
to such lengths to rig the evidence?

495
00:27:16,291 --> 00:27:17,750
Looking at it from another angle,

496
00:27:17,833 --> 00:27:19,625
it suggests he thinks
the case is legally weak.

497
00:27:21,875 --> 00:27:22,708
[Ms. Iemori] So…

498
00:27:23,541 --> 00:27:26,000
It's important to win
without having to fight.

499
00:27:26,708 --> 00:27:28,541
A lesson my mentor taught me.

500
00:27:28,625 --> 00:27:29,666
[music ends]

501
00:27:30,458 --> 00:27:34,250
So Mr. Yamashiro has lost the battle
before it started.

502
00:27:35,458 --> 00:27:38,916
Really, though,
you are such a rude young man.

503
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:40,916
- Get those things off the desk.
- Oh.

504
00:27:41,958 --> 00:27:42,791
Yes, yes.

505
00:27:43,291 --> 00:27:45,041
One "yes" will do.

506
00:27:48,875 --> 00:27:50,708
Shoes on the desk…

507
00:27:50,791 --> 00:27:51,625
[angry chatter]

508
00:27:51,708 --> 00:27:54,791
[man 1] What the hell is going on?
This totally sucks.

509
00:27:54,875 --> 00:27:58,208
[man 2] I don't know. I heard
some idiots are fighting with security.

510
00:27:58,291 --> 00:28:00,625
[man 1] Hey, let us in! Hey!

511
00:28:01,125 --> 00:28:02,708
I'm calling the cops!

512
00:28:03,250 --> 00:28:05,166
I said let us in! Hey!

513
00:28:05,250 --> 00:28:06,125
Get out of the way.

514
00:28:06,208 --> 00:28:07,166
[man 1] Huh?

515
00:28:07,250 --> 00:28:08,916
[tense music playing]

516
00:28:21,541 --> 00:28:23,541
[upbeat music playing]

517
00:28:30,500 --> 00:28:31,333
[man grunts]

518
00:28:31,416 --> 00:28:32,666
[Sugawara] There we go.

519
00:28:32,750 --> 00:28:34,541
- [man cries out]
- [Sugawara grunts]

520
00:28:36,208 --> 00:28:37,666
[Sugawara] Mibu.

521
00:28:38,666 --> 00:28:40,208
What took you?

522
00:28:41,625 --> 00:28:42,625
So tell me…

523
00:28:43,125 --> 00:28:45,000
What've you been teaching your crew?

524
00:28:47,166 --> 00:28:49,750
They knew I was backing this joint
and came at it anyway?

525
00:28:51,416 --> 00:28:52,666
No, sir.

526
00:28:53,416 --> 00:28:55,125
Not so, Mr. Sugawara.

527
00:28:55,708 --> 00:28:58,541
You guys messed with
my business interests.

528
00:29:00,166 --> 00:29:01,041
Ah…

529
00:29:03,750 --> 00:29:05,208
What do you say to that?

530
00:29:06,500 --> 00:29:07,750
I'm sorry.

531
00:29:09,083 --> 00:29:09,916
Huh?

532
00:29:10,875 --> 00:29:12,458
I didn't catch that.

533
00:29:13,541 --> 00:29:15,291
You sound insincere.

534
00:29:16,750 --> 00:29:19,166
Get on your knees and apologize to me.

535
00:29:21,541 --> 00:29:23,625
[man groans]

536
00:29:23,708 --> 00:29:25,083
Mr. Mibu…

537
00:29:26,333 --> 00:29:27,208
[groans]

538
00:29:27,291 --> 00:29:29,208
If you don't, I'll break his legs.

539
00:29:29,791 --> 00:29:31,125
Here. [grunts]

540
00:29:31,208 --> 00:29:33,500
[man groans]

541
00:29:36,083 --> 00:29:38,458
My subordinate was disrespectful to you.

542
00:29:40,916 --> 00:29:42,625
I'm sorry. Please forgive us.

543
00:29:42,708 --> 00:29:43,708
Mr. Mibu!

544
00:29:43,791 --> 00:29:45,541
[laughs]

545
00:29:45,625 --> 00:29:46,916
Pathetic little worms.

546
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:48,500
[laughs]

547
00:29:48,583 --> 00:29:50,125
Kuga, are you filming this?

548
00:29:50,208 --> 00:29:51,333
Yes, sir. I am.

549
00:30:02,208 --> 00:30:04,625
Five million for the inconvenience.

550
00:30:06,041 --> 00:30:07,000
Deliver it.

551
00:30:08,916 --> 00:30:10,208
Mibu.

552
00:30:11,416 --> 00:30:13,125
[cracking]

553
00:30:16,416 --> 00:30:23,416
IEMORI

554
00:30:25,958 --> 00:30:28,875
Saeko,
thank you for helping me deal with this.

555
00:30:29,375 --> 00:30:32,333
The estate cleaners can deal with
the rest of the belongings.

556
00:30:33,083 --> 00:30:34,458
[Saeko] Hanae.

557
00:30:34,541 --> 00:30:36,875
What are these, photo albums?

558
00:30:38,583 --> 00:30:39,416
Here. Take 'em.

559
00:30:43,666 --> 00:30:45,333
Hey. Before he died,

560
00:30:45,416 --> 00:30:47,750
you received a living trust
of 25 million, right?

561
00:30:47,833 --> 00:30:49,541
What did you do with it?

562
00:30:49,625 --> 00:30:52,666
The whole thing went to the fees
for Dad's nursing care.

563
00:30:52,750 --> 00:30:53,666
What?

564
00:30:53,750 --> 00:30:57,416
You spent 25 million
on nursing care fees? I can't believe it.

565
00:30:57,916 --> 00:30:59,541
That's what it costs.

566
00:30:59,625 --> 00:31:02,791
I would know since I had to make
all the arrangements by myself.

567
00:31:03,375 --> 00:31:05,708
Oh, sure, sure.

568
00:31:05,791 --> 00:31:08,208
You made all the arrangements by yourself,

569
00:31:08,291 --> 00:31:10,958
so that's why you chose
such a cheap nursing home.

570
00:31:11,041 --> 00:31:12,458
It wasn't cheap.

571
00:31:12,541 --> 00:31:14,291
[scoffs] Oh yeah?

572
00:31:14,375 --> 00:31:17,666
This article online called it
a garbage can for gramps.

573
00:31:18,750 --> 00:31:22,541
So then you used the money you saved
to get yourself some massages?

574
00:31:22,625 --> 00:31:24,291
I heard it from the neighbors.

575
00:31:24,791 --> 00:31:26,125
And what's wrong with that?

576
00:31:26,208 --> 00:31:28,500
There I was, working, taking care of him,

577
00:31:28,583 --> 00:31:31,208
getting by on four hours of sleep a night.

578
00:31:32,250 --> 00:31:33,083
[sighs]

579
00:31:33,166 --> 00:31:36,541
Well, I suppose a housewife
like you wouldn't understand.

580
00:31:37,166 --> 00:31:38,291
Watch it.

581
00:31:39,125 --> 00:31:41,375
How dare you look down on housewives?

582
00:31:41,875 --> 00:31:44,125
You let the nursing home
steal the inheritance.

583
00:31:44,625 --> 00:31:45,625
If that's what you think,

584
00:31:45,708 --> 00:31:47,333
why didn't the two of you
take care of him?

585
00:31:47,416 --> 00:31:50,208
Why should I have to look after
my father-in-law?

586
00:31:50,291 --> 00:31:53,333
It was me who helped your mother
use the bathroom in the end, you know.

587
00:31:53,416 --> 00:31:56,208
And how much money do you think
I gave you for living expenses?

588
00:31:56,291 --> 00:31:58,041
Oh please, enough!

589
00:31:58,125 --> 00:32:01,083
I could have had
a totally different life, sister.

590
00:32:01,625 --> 00:32:04,416
Your mother nagged me day and night,
but I still put up with it.

591
00:32:05,250 --> 00:32:06,458
Anyway,

592
00:32:06,541 --> 00:32:08,500
you'd better get back
our share of the inheritance

593
00:32:08,583 --> 00:32:10,333
so I can have what I deserve.

594
00:32:12,291 --> 00:32:15,791
Seriously… [whispering] …I can't believe
all the work I put in this family.

595
00:32:17,666 --> 00:32:18,583
[sighs]

596
00:32:23,750 --> 00:32:24,791
[groans]

597
00:32:27,750 --> 00:32:29,083
I'm so tired.

598
00:32:43,416 --> 00:32:45,708
HANAE, 6 YEARS OLD
KEISUKE, 4 YEARS OLD

599
00:32:45,791 --> 00:32:52,416
AUGUST 7TH AT HACHIOJI AMUSEMENT PARK

600
00:32:56,125 --> 00:32:59,791
AMUSEMENT PARK TICKET ADULT: 700 YEN

601
00:33:05,666 --> 00:33:07,666
[music box tinkling]

602
00:33:43,208 --> 00:33:45,083
[Mibu chuckles]

603
00:33:45,166 --> 00:33:46,750
Something smells really good around here.

604
00:33:46,833 --> 00:33:48,250
[Kujo] Hey, Mibu.

605
00:33:48,875 --> 00:33:50,625
- Some freshly smoked meat.
- [Mibu] Oh.

606
00:33:50,708 --> 00:33:52,083
[Kujo] Would you like to join us?

607
00:33:52,166 --> 00:33:53,750
- [Mibu] You sure?
- [Kujo] Of course.

608
00:33:56,875 --> 00:33:58,291
Then I'll give it a try.

609
00:33:58,375 --> 00:33:59,250
Huh?

610
00:33:59,833 --> 00:34:00,916
[Kujo laughs]

611
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:02,708
You're really tearing into it!

612
00:34:02,791 --> 00:34:03,625
[Mibu] Mmm.

613
00:34:09,583 --> 00:34:10,416
[Kujo sighs]

614
00:34:10,500 --> 00:34:13,333
There's nothing like
an afternoon beer on the roof.

615
00:34:14,375 --> 00:34:15,750
It's the best.

616
00:34:18,625 --> 00:34:19,500
[exhales]

617
00:34:22,208 --> 00:34:23,291
Attorney…

618
00:34:27,500 --> 00:34:28,666
here you go.

619
00:34:29,875 --> 00:34:31,375
[upbeat music playing]

620
00:34:32,166 --> 00:34:34,333
Thank you. I appreciate it.

621
00:34:35,750 --> 00:34:39,125
[Mibu] Well, I have some things
to take care of, so I'll be going now.

622
00:34:39,666 --> 00:34:40,958
Thanks for the food.

623
00:34:50,125 --> 00:34:51,250
Thanks a lot.

624
00:34:51,333 --> 00:34:52,166
Uh.

625
00:35:16,416 --> 00:35:19,833
Mr. Kujo,
what's the deal with the USB drive?

626
00:35:21,291 --> 00:35:23,416
Our ace in the hole
for Attorney Yamashiro.

627
00:35:23,500 --> 00:35:24,958
To catch him off guard.

628
00:35:28,500 --> 00:35:29,375
[exhales]

629
00:35:29,458 --> 00:35:30,583
Um…

630
00:35:31,250 --> 00:35:32,750
I've gotta ask you again.

631
00:35:34,416 --> 00:35:35,416
Go ahead.

632
00:35:36,041 --> 00:35:39,875
Why did you insist on
going up against Attorney Yamashiro,

633
00:35:39,958 --> 00:35:41,250
even though he was your mentor?

634
00:35:43,458 --> 00:35:46,791
I'm just working to defend
my client's best interests.

635
00:35:47,291 --> 00:35:49,333
Yamashiro's views, unfortunately,

636
00:35:49,416 --> 00:35:52,250
happen to be at odds
with those of my client.

637
00:35:53,916 --> 00:35:55,541
Views that are at odds…

638
00:36:00,583 --> 00:36:05,000
Supposing our views happened
to be at odds for some reason.

639
00:36:05,708 --> 00:36:08,333
We'd go up against each other too, right?

640
00:36:18,708 --> 00:36:20,375
Don't say scary things like that.

641
00:36:28,041 --> 00:36:29,208
You want some coffee?

642
00:36:30,375 --> 00:36:31,416
Yes, please.

643
00:36:42,708 --> 00:36:44,583
[Sugawara] <i>Hello, Attorney Yamashiro?</i>

644
00:36:45,541 --> 00:36:47,208
<i>Did you see the news?</i>

645
00:36:47,291 --> 00:36:48,583
Yes.

646
00:36:51,791 --> 00:36:55,041
ABUSE RAMPANT AT CHIBA NURSING HOME
TOEI SHIMBUN ONLINE

647
00:36:58,166 --> 00:37:00,166
Kujo, huh?

648
00:37:00,666 --> 00:37:01,875
[sneezes]

649
00:37:03,708 --> 00:37:05,375
Which pollen's bugging you now?

650
00:37:06,541 --> 00:37:09,375
At this time of year,
it could be ragweed or rice, or…

651
00:37:10,416 --> 00:37:13,583
Someone could be talking about me,
I guess.

652
00:37:23,333 --> 00:37:26,375
ABUSE RAMPANT AT CHIBA NURSING HOME
TOEI SHIMBUN ONLINE

653
00:37:26,458 --> 00:37:28,875
AS A FORM OF “DISCIPLINE”

654
00:37:28,958 --> 00:37:32,791
A FLICK TO THE BROKEN RIB

655
00:37:32,875 --> 00:37:35,625
ABUSE RAMPANT AT CHIBA NURSING HOME
TOEI SHIMBUN ONLINE

656
00:37:42,166 --> 00:37:44,458
[man] <i>How many times</i>
<i>do you have to screw it up?</i>

657
00:37:44,541 --> 00:37:46,125
<i>C'mon! Hurry up. Write it.</i>

658
00:37:46,208 --> 00:37:48,875
<i>- C'mon, c'mon, c'mon, c'mon!</i>
- [Mr. Iemori moans]

659
00:37:48,958 --> 00:37:50,750
[man] <i>Come on, get on with it!</i>

660
00:37:50,833 --> 00:37:52,666
[Mr. Iemori crying]

661
00:37:52,750 --> 00:37:54,708
[man] <i>No, that’s not how we do it.</i>

662
00:37:55,208 --> 00:37:56,333
[Mr. Iemori sobbing]

663
00:37:56,416 --> 00:37:59,041
[man] <i>Start from the beginning.</i>
<i>Get it right this time.</i>

664
00:38:00,541 --> 00:38:02,541
[closing theme song playing]

665
00:40:38,291 --> 00:40:39,500
[music fades]
